@node editorsdesk "From The Editor's Desk"
@toc contents
============================================================================
	            @{b}From The Editor's Desk@{ub} - by: @{"Timo Paul" link timopaul}
============================================================================

  Happy holidays, I hope that you are sitting comfortably and in a warm
  place reading this issue of WhatIFF? First off I must apologise for
  the lateness of this issue, due to some maintenance work on our home I
  have not had access to my Amiga and then afterwards going to Okinawa for
  a few days (Ahem). We have some fantastic contributions and interviews 
  this issue with @{"Steve Lord" link stevelord} back with an indepth
  guide about viewing YouTube videos on your AGA Amigas. @{"Ivan Sorensen" link ivansorensen}
  has written about the Amiga in 2022, we have interviews with PixelVixen
  and Anthony of The Amiga Show. @{"John Scolieri" link johnscolieri} has a
  review on a Dell LED monitor that is compatible with the standard Amiga
  resolutions.

  This is also our first year as a magazine, it is incredible how the time
  has flown by. I have greatly enjoyed working on the magazine and seeing
  how it has grown over the last year with new writers and content. I have
  new respect for the writers of Amiga Future and Amiga Addict, I have 
  found it a tiring but rewarding job, though it has not been nice to my 
  wallet and as such it is considerably thinner since starting the 
  magazine. The Amiga scene has really grown this year with a lot  of new 
  hardware and games being released, alongside some productive 
  applications.

  It is going to be an interesting 2023 and hopefully we will be there with
  you, who knows how long the magazine will be around but there is hope 
  that we might do a limited print run sometime in the future, more on that 
  next year. In the meantime enjoy this issue, make sure you read 
  @{"Kevin Saunders" link kevinsaunders} Invents Corner page for the latest on his 
  projects. 

  Take care, thank you for having joined us for this year and see you in 
  2023.  Before I go I just want to thank everyone who has written for the 
  magazine this year, especially:

  @{"Steve Lord" link stevelord}, @{"Kevin Saunders" link kevinsaunders}, @{"John Scolieri" link johnscolieri}
  and @{"Ivan Sorensen" link ivansorensen} who have all been regular contributors
  putting up kindly with my constant nagging for articles and updates.

  See you all in 2023!
      
@endnode

@node shelltalk "Free For All About The Amiga"
@toc contents
============================================================================
	               @{b}Shell Talk@{ub} - by: @{"Vicky Lamburn" link vickylamburn} 
============================================================================

  I guess it can be summed up like this, and this may be contentious but 
  I'm beyond caring: I don't use retro computers to relive the past, I use 
  them now to create new experiences for the now and to create the future. 
  I'm sick of all the "How I remember the day" and "Are you this old?" 
  bullshit everywhere on the internet, I think this is in a big way why I 
  began to slink back from participating in the retro scene as it's way too 
  backwards looking for my liking. I love old games but not because they're 
  old, but because they bring me joy in the present.

  And also, like yeah, the Amiga was a big failure in the end compared to 
  the PC and Mac really (or it would still be a mainstream system) but what 
  a beautiful fuck up it was! Instead of fighting old wars and old 
  arguments (including telling me the Amiga wasn't a fuck up because in 
  1988 it was everywhere or the A500 sold a million) we should just use it 
  now and enjoy it and push it in new ways to create a new future for it. 
  I don't give a shit about whether an Amiga 1200 in 1993 was competitive 
  to a 386SX, that doesn't matter and never really did, but so much of the 
  retro scene is about that kind of stodgy bullshit.

  I'd just rather use the Amiga now amongst everything else because it's 
  rad, I use it to push the creative envelope in 2022 in a mainstream kinda 
  way, not just in demo comps or on retro YouTube channels. If I could one 
  day hook up with someone who was good at music production, create actual 
  animated anime and merge it with Amiga HAM animation, stills etc. it'd be 
  so sick. I can dream big but one day I'd love to be be launching my manga 
  with a visual DJ event incorporating all that. But seeing as I only have 
  10 readers, I have to keep dreaming.

  I think the one way the old stuff is more interesting is that now it's so 
  punk, compared to all that commodified stuff in a Mac or Windows or even 
  Linux. It's like the world is being drained of its imagination as it 
  stares endlessly down the infinite scroll of the matrix. So I like using 
  old stuff in the present to start disrupting consensus, merge analogue 
  and digital and make something new for now and the future. The world 
  could change tomorrow if everyone deleted their social media and told the 
  Silicon Valley god incarnates to fuck off but then if their is one hope 
  for the metaverse is that Zuckerberg gets so sucked into it he never 
  reappears. All those billions to create him a new ass to disappear up! :)

  My only other thing I want to say to other creatives is think how the 
  Amiga can contribute to wider projects, don't think it all has to be 
  performed through the Amiga. Pete Cannon does this so well with his music
  as does Paulee Bow; this isn't to take away from what CTrix and Hoffman 
  do with just the Amiga. Actually on that note, that's what I want to 
  continue seeing more of, not Sysinfo screenshots and the Frontier intro, 
  but generally more Amiga derived creativity, this is what is enticing 
  about the demo scene but that again is system limited. This isn't meant 
  to be a dig at the tinkerers and modders but I'd love to see some of 
  that power used to creative ends not just as stat waggling.

  Anyway, the future isn't in the past, it's always ahead of you, so run 
  to it and don't look back.

@endnode

