@node amigalcdmonitorreview
@toc reviews
============================================================================
         @{b}15Khz Compatible LCD Monitor Review @{ub} - by @{"John Scolieri" link johnscolieri}
============================================================================

  #Modern 15KHz monitor that works with Amiga

  I'm lucky that I have an Amiga 1080 CRT monitor in my man cave that still
  works great but it's still a pain in the you know what to disconnect it 
  from my Amiga 1000 when I need to trouble shoot or test another Amiga so 
  I was very happy when I recetnly stumbled on a used monitor that was for 
  sale at a local electronic store that was adverised as a 'multi-sync' 
  monitor.

  The monitor is a DELL U2412M LED monitor with VGA, DVI, and HDMI 
  connectors. I hooked it up to my Amiga 1200 with an RGB to VGA adapter 
  and VGA cable that I had lying around and was pleasantly surpised when 
  the early start up menu popped up on the screen with no fiddling of 
  settings etc...it just worked.

  In Workbench all my games and applications worked just fine (including 
  Lightwave/ Modeler and render screens) after adjusting my overscan 
  screens to adjust for the 16x10 format. Games run smooth with no 
  artifacts or tearing and colours are bright and crisp. 

  I also tested the following screen modes:

  - DBLPal- ok
  - DBLNTSC- ok
  - Multisync Productivity- ok
  - Super 72- not working
  - Euro36- not working
  - Euro72- not working

  Interlaced modes worked but with a noticeable flicker though so basically 
  unusable without a flicker fixer.

  Overall I'm very happy with this monitor for my Amiga use and it's also 
  nice to use it with my work notebook as well via HDMI cable when I'm 
  working from home.

@endnode


@node a1200netcasereview "A1200.net - A1200 Translucent Replacement Case Review"
@toc reviews
============================================================================
    @{b}A1200.net - A1200 Translucent Replacement Case Review@{ub} - by @{"Timo Paul" link timopaul}
============================================================================

  ##Product Name
  A1200.net Replacement Case

  ##Available From
  www.amigastore.eu
  www.amigaonthelake.com
  www.retrokit.com.au
  www.micromiga.com
  www.retropassion.co.uk
  www.amiga-shop.net (Alinea)
  www.vesalia.de
  www.amedia-computer.com
  
  ##Price
  USD 120 / EUR 99 / GBP 105 (Inc. 20% VAT)

  ##Hardware/Software Requirements
  A1200
 
  ##A New Home For Your Amiga
  
  Over the years my A1200 has gradually been upgraded in one form or 
  another through, CAPS having been replaced, an Indivision AGA MK3, 
  TF1260, GOTEK drive and replacement LEDs installed.
 
  All of the changes have been internal and through this the case has been 
  opened and closed numerous times, as such it has become a bit rough 
  around the edges with the bottom half featuring a crack and all the tabs 
  at the back broken. It still looks white but the wear and tear from 
  constantly being opened and closed have taken it's toll, as such I 
  decided it was time to re-house the venerable Amiga into something 
  more fetching. 

  There were two options available to me, find an original case or buy one 
  of the new ones created by A1200.net. After a search on eBay it became 
  quickly clear that buying an A1200.net was the cheaper option.

  If you have not heard of the A1200.net cases, it was a Kickstarter that
  begun in 2016, after a successful initial fund the cases became available 
  to the general public.

  ##More Than Just A Case

  The cases however go beyond the standard A1200 housing, some of the 
  features of these newer casings are as follows:

  * Made by injection molding
  * Enhanced rear door
  * Vents on the bottom trap door
  * Rubber feet
  * Set of brass screws
  * CF Slot above the PCMCIA slot for HD access
  * Pre-cut GOTEK LED panel
  * Two USB slots on the right
  * Available in different colours
  * UV Protection to stop the dreaded yellowing
  * Metal brass inserts to stop dimples and screw holes breaking  
  
  As you can see these cases offer more than the traditional case and it is
  particulary useful for the modern Amiga 1200 user since quite a few if 
  not the majortiy of users have upgraded their machines with a variety of
  modern enhancements.

  Originally the cases were only available from A1200.net luckily for us
  they can be bought from a number of Amiga vendors. For my case I went 
  with Alinea, however they are also available from the following Amiga
  vendors:

  * www.amigastore.eu
  * www.amigaonthelake.com
  * www.retrokit.com.au
  * www.micromiga.com
  * www.retropassion.co.uk
  * www.amiga-shop.net (Alinea)
  * www.vesalia.de
  * www.amedia-computer.com

  Being in Japan I had to choose a vendor that gave me a better rate for
  my yen to whatever currency I bought the case for. In the end I chose
  Alinea since they had the best price and cheapest shipping option, plus
  they were the only vendor to still have the translucent casing that I 
  was after. After a quick process of setting up an account and making a
  payment via PayPal all I had to do was sit back and wait. Credit must
  given to Alinea for their fast processing, the day after my order had 
  been put in, it had already been packed and shipped. Taking only around a 
  week to arrive I had to quickly prepare my A1200 for it's new home.

  A week later and Japan Post delivered the slim box, luckily I did not
  have to pay any import charges. The box itself comes in a charming and
  nostalgic A1200 box, it is very reminiscent of the original A1200 box all
  Amiga 1200s used to come in. After opening the box I was presented with 
  the case in a plastic bag, and two other bags containing the screws and
  3 x back plates and trap door. Initial impressions were good, it felt
  nice with a textured feel that at least seems to be missing from my 
  original A1200 case. The plastic seemed a little more flexible than the
  my A1200 case but at the same time stronger, it was easy to see where the 
  case can be easily cut for the extra USB ports, GOTEK and CF slot. So 
  enough admiring of the new case, onto the installation ...

  ##Moving Time

  Removing the Amiga motherboard was a simple task of taking off the top
  lid, unscrewing 3 screws to motherboard (at least in my case) and then 
  sliding it out. It was rather alarming seeing how much dust and dirt had
  managed to get into the housing. Sliding the A1200 motherboard into the
  new case was a simple task without any hitches. Once the board was 
  screwed in it was time to attach the Indivision AGA MK3 board, the case
  comes with several back door flaps for those who have a VGA or DVI cable
  coming out the back. However this was my first disappointment with the
  case, the VGA/HDMI adapter of the Indivision screws into a hole on the
  original A1200 case allowing the adapter to sit nice and snuggly however
  the A1200.net case rear door panel is not oriented correctly for the 
  Indivision ports which means if you want to use it with the new case you
  will have to find another way to secure the video port. In my case I used
  some double sided tape but I felt it was a bit of let down since one of
  the reasons for buying the case was the have the Indivision snuggly 
  installed. Hopefully this is something that can be updated in future
  versions. After installation of the Indivision I was able to close the up
  the Amiga. It was here that I really appreciated the new screw inserts
  also the rear now has three other long screws to close the case instead 
  of the weaker tabs. It was nice to be able to screw the Amiga tightly 
  without having to worry about the plastic breaking or dimples appearing.

  ##How Does She Look?   

  As this is more of a cosmetic upgrade for the Amiga you are most 
  interested in how it looks. Well, I was very pleased with how my Amiga
  looks now. The translucent/skeleton/see through case looks fantastic, 
  even with my original keyboard which I had whitened last year the overall
  effect is very pleasing to the eye. You can just about see the chips on
  the motherboard but it gets even more fun when you turn on the Amiga and
  the hard disk, floppy and power lights come on, they help luminate the
  inside of the Amiga enchanced by the translucent case.

  I really enjoy pulling my Amiga out from my desk to see it in it's new
  case, the photos online do not give it justice to how good the Amiga 
  looks in a translucent case. There was one other issue after putting the
  Amiga together however. The PCMCIA slot seems to be 1-2 mmm offset which
  means when inserting a card you are unable to slot it in straight. To 
  make it go in you need to come at an angle and slowly jiggle it in. I had
  double checked my installation of the A1200 motherboard after this but 
  could see no issue with the installation, most likely this is a 
  manufacturing error. Over time it seems like the motherboard has settled 
  into the case though and it has become easier to insert the card but I 
  still have to make sure I do it at an angle.
  
  ##Final Conclusions

  The A1200.net cases are a great way to give your Amigas a facelift, they
  offer more expansion opportunities and look fantastic. If it was not for
  the VGA/DVI back plate/Indivision connector issue and PCMCIA slot 
  misalignment this would be a perfect product. It is built very well, the
  addition of metal scew inserts, replacement of rear tabs for screws and
  the grilled trapdoor all make it not an essential purchase but one that
  is highly recommended. If you want to change the look of your Amiga or
  your case has become a bit rough around the edges then these cases are
  for you.

  ##Pros and Cons

  + Variety of colours
  + More durable than the original cases
  + Goes beyond a tradition case with different backing plates, grilled
    trap door and metal screw inserts
  + Not too expensive
  - Rear trapdoor and bottom case do not accomodate the Indivision
    correctly
  - PCMCIA slot not aligned properly
  
  ## Scores

  Ease Of Use: 8
  Features: 8  
  Value For money: 8
  Overall: 80% - WhatIFF? Silver 
  
@endnode

@node rnoeffectsreview "RNO Effects_68K Review"
@toc reviews
============================================================================
	    	  @{b}RNO Effects_68K Review@{ub} - by: @{"Timo Paul" link timopaul}
============================================================================

  ##Product Name
  RNOEffects_68K

  ##Available From
  www.aminet.net
  
  ##Price
  Free

  ##Hardware/Software Requirements
  Amigs OS 3.0+, minimum 68020 and fast ram
  MUI, TextEditor.mcc, codesets, guigfx, render, and reqtools libs

  ##Image Processing Is Back

  If you were to think of the best image processing software on the Amiga
  most people will probably mention ImageFX or ADPro. Of these two only
  ImageFX has been updated and that was still a few years back, since then
  we have not had any real challenges to the ImageFX dominance. However
  there is a program that has been available for free for a while now and 
  does a lot of what ImageFX can do and all for free.

  RNOEffects is available for classic Amigas, OS4 and Morph OS, for this 
  review I will concentrate on the 68K version as I do not have an OS4 or
  Morph machine to hand. The software has 30 image processing effects which
  include drop shadows, emboss, various colour filters and drawing options
  for various shapes and text. It is also effecient as a batch iage 
  convertor.

  ##Installation

  The installation of RNOEffects is quite involved (for classic systems) 
  and it took me a while to download everything and figure out where each 
  of additional downloads went. Definitely reading the documenation is 
  highly recommended before even trying to load RNOEffects. The extra 
  installs with the links are as follows:

  - MUI 3.8 or later (http://aminet.net/package/util/libs/mui38usr)
  - TextEditor.mcc (http://aminet.net/search?query=mcc+texteditor)
  - codesets.library (http://aminet.net/search?query=codesets)
  - guigfx.library (http://aminet.net/package/dev/misc/guigfxlib)
  - render.library (http://aminet.net/search?query=renderlib), v32 is 
    probably the best for <040 CPUs
  - reqtools.library (http://aminet.net/package/util/libs/ReqToolsLib)

  Once you have downloaded and installed the above items it is just a 
  simple case of copying the drawer over to a location of your choice. Of 
  the extra installs I found TextEditor most difficult to install since you 
  need to find the MUI install drawer, show all files, locate the 'Libs' 
  drawer, then go to the drawer named MUI and copy the mcc files. The other
  libraries had installers making it easier but it just shows how important
  it is to read the documentation, especially with software that is 
  available from Aminet. 

  After a some time spent downloading and installing the libraries and 
  components I was ready to go.

  ##In Use

  There is a slight delay in loading the program but once it is up you are
  presented with a window, containing three main buttons 'O' - open, 
  'P' - previous & 'N' next. It was a little confusing at first as I have
  imagined 'P' - print and 'N' - new. There are arrow buttons on the right
  which will be greyed out until you have applied an effect as these act
  as undo and redo. 
  
  Overall it is very a sparse and utilitarian window that opens up on your 
  Workbench. As such whatever image is displayed will be limited to the 
  Workbench screen depth. Most of the effects are accessed via the drop 
  down menu. From here you have access to various filters/processing 
  effects that along with saving formats. You can save files in: PNG, JPEG, 
  GIF, ILBM, and BMP along with all Amiga icon formats. The list of effects 
  that can be applied are as follows:

   * Background Colour		* Modulate		* Shadow	
   * Blur			* Monochrom             * Sharpen
   * Charcoal                   * Oil Paint             * Solarize
   * Contrast                   * Opacity Map           * Swirl
   * Crop                       * Perspective           * Tint
   * Draw                       * Pixelate              * Water Ripple
   * Edge                       * Polar Distort
   * Emboss                     * Quantize
   * Flip                       * Reduce Alpha
   * Gama                       * Resize
   * Invert                     * Rotate

  As you can see there are quite a number of effects that can be applied, 
  and each effect has it's own parameters window. It can take some time
  to apply an effect and there is no progress indicator/bar common in most
  modern Amiga software. As such it can appear as if your Amiga has stopped 
  working or the effect has not been applied. Due to being on the Workbench 
  screen it was a little hard to gauge the effectiveness of the applied 
  filter. This was evident when I applied a 'Charcoal' filter and during 
  the application of the filter I was given no indicatiton that the program 
  was working.

  There are lot of options for each of the effects and it pays off to have
  proper look at each of the effects.

  It would be nice to have the effects sorted into different categories, 
  having them lumped all together makes it a little harder trying to find 
  a specific filter.

  ##Overall Impressions

  RNOEffect is a good image effects processor that has some advanced 
  features, and is very impressive for a free product. There is not much 
  that you can't do with it but you do need to spend some time figuring out 
  how to use/apply the effects properly. There is video on YouTube to help 
  you get the hang of RNOEffects: 

  https://youtu.be/KsRtDHXkEKA 
  
  There are just a few issues that stop it from being a really great 
  product. It is quite a journey from downloading the software to getting 
  it up and running, there are a lot of libraries and components that need 
  to be installed and you might run into some problems initially. It seems
  that if you are running OS4.1 or Morph OS the installation however is a 
  much simpler affair. 
  
  One bug that I did encounter was when opening a file in an unrecognised
  format, RNOEffects will suddenly close without any warning. Hopefully 
  this will be addressed in a future update.

  It feels like a program that was made for more powerful computers, as 
  such it is probably a much better experience on an OS4 or Morph OS 
  machine. As it stands running it on a classic machines feels a bit 
  slugglish, and I found myself going back to ImageFX 2 since it is more 
  responsive and is able to handle a larger variety of file formatse. 
  
  ##Final Thoughts
  
  RNOEffects is a great idea hampered by a time consuming installation,
  difficult user interface and lack of resolution/screen modes. If you 
  have an Amiga with a video card or a newer OS such as an OS4/MorphOS then 
  RNOEeffects will be come an essential tool. It's batch processing and 
  large variety of effects make it a valuable graphics utility. However 
  with older software like ImageFX easily available and more suited to the 
  classic hardware I feel less inclined to recommend this to classic users 
  and more to Amiga owners with 24Bit displays or the newer OS systems. 
 
  Download it and have a play around but I recommend having lots of ram, a 
  fast processor and if possible a graphics card.

  ##Pros and Cons

  + New FREE image processor
  + Large variety of effects
  + Batch processing
  - Very slow on 68K Amigas 
  - Really needs a 24Bit display
  - UI could be better
  
@endnode

@node aminettasters "Aminet Tasters - A quick dip into the latest updates of software available on Aminet."
@toc reviews
============================================================================
                          @{b}- Aminet Tasters -@{ub}
============================================================================

  Welcome to the Aminet Tasters section, here we dip into the latest 
  uploads of interest. We do not have time to cover everything uploaded, so
  this is just a random selection of uploads that caught our interest. This 
  month there have been some standard updates and useful tools for users of 
  older Commodore computers.

  ------------------------------------------------------------------------ 

  ##D-CAPS Stomper
  www.aminet.net/package/mus/edit/D-CAPS-Stomper

  A great little program for creating your own kick drums, opens up onto
  to your Workbench allowing you to tweak until your are content with the
  your custom kickdrum. Unfortunately there is no way to preview the audio
  on the Amiga. I contacted the author and at the moment there are no
  plans to fix this. The only way to hear your custom kickdrum is to load
  it into a DAW.

  ##AmiSSL 5.5
  www.aminet.net/package/util/libs/AmiSSL-5.5-OS3

  Another update to the ever useful AmiSSL now on version 5.5, this version
  brings full compatability with OpenSSL 3.0, important security related
  fixes, a built in HTTP(S) client and comes with the latest encryption
  ciphers. If you surf the net with your Amiga then updating to this the
  latest version should be no brainer.

  ##GeoWrite Import
  www.aminet.net/package/util/conv/gwimport

  For those who wish to transfer their GeoWrite documents to their Amiga,
  this utility will convert a GeoWrite file into an ASCII file to be
  read on an Amiga. Reqtools.libary is needed to run the utility. It is
  a useful utility that runs easily, a good program to have sitting on
  your HD if you still use GeoWrite. 
  
  ##WebP Image Datatype V45.4
  www.aminet.net/package/util/dtype/WarpWebPdt

  Update to the WebP Image datatype, this version fixes crashes on 020 and
  030 computers. Gives you more control over how images will be displayed
  on your browser, can turn off dithering for 16Bit+ displays, handles
  both lossless and lossy WebP images.

  ##Icon Libary V46.4
  www.aminet.net/package/util/libs/IconLib_46.4
 
  Latest version of the free optomized icon replacement library, this 
  update fixes a problem with the patch SetMan and a workaround for
  another issue. Good for Amiga OS 3.0-3.9, however I had some issues
  with Kickstart 3.2 and ClassicWB. 

  ##IMP v3.382
  www.aminet.net/package/mus/play/imp3

  Juen keeps improving and updating his fantastic MOD streamer for all
  Amiga models.  With this version it can be used with an IMPBox. If
  you still have not downloaded this incredible piece of software do
  it now!

  ##Hippo Player Update v2.55
  www.aminet.net/package/mus/play/hippoplayerupdate

  One of my favourite audio players, nice and compact with great features.
  With the latest update you get the ability to drag'and'drop folders and 
  all of the fonts can be changed in the main window. The feature that I
  find most interesting is the ability to search and download from some
  module websites.
  
  ##Versatile Amiga Test Program
  www.aminet.net/uti/misc/VATestprogram.zip

  Another Amiga test program for our Amigas, this one is from Jochem 
  Caspers and is a nice little program for finding out what is wrong with
  your Amiga. This update allows for more indepth Bob testing and can
  identify your model of Vampire V2 under ChipID.

