@node agaconvpart1 "Watch YouTube Videos On AGA Amigas Part 1"
@toc guides
=============================================================================
    @{b}Watch YouTube Videos On Your Amiga Pt: 1 AGA Users@{ub} - by: @{"Steve Lord" link stevelord}
=============================================================================

  # Watching YouTube Videos On Your Amiga Pt 1: AGA Users

  The Amiga Show is a beautiful YouTube series. A labour of love all about 
  the Amiga, produced entirely on the Amiga. It'd be great to be able to 
  watch the show on the Amiga, and using some Open Source tools, you can. 
  This article focuses on AGAConv and AGABlaster on AGA Amigas - The A1200, 
  A4000, and with a nod to the CD32. A future article will look at options 
  for OCS and ECS Amigas, while a 3rd part will look at other tools and 
  codecs.

  ## No MPEG, No Problem!

  Probably the most well-known 90s video codec is MPEG-1, as used in the 
  old Video CD format. Other codecs such as QuikPak and Sorenson were also 
  popular with Mac users. You might not know that among the many 
  innovations Commodore threw away, CDXL was one of the first full-motion 
  video file formats. The now-expired patent 
  (available at https://www.freepatentsonline.com/5293606.html) 
  demonstrates how CDXL works, tightly coupled to the Amiga's chipset and 
  DMA capabilities.

  As with many Amiga technologies, CDXL gave way to newer formats and 
  software. Markus Schordan started playing with HAM video and eventually 
  created AGAConv and AGABlaster, which are far and away the best ways to 
  watch video on classic Amigas.

  As well as AGABlaster, AmiTube - available at 
  https://blog.alb42.de/programs/amitube/ is a GUI tool for downloading and 
  playing YouTube videos from your Amiga. AmiTube is great for short clips, 
  but requires substantial server resources for transcoding. I wouldn't use 
  it for anything long like The Amiga Show. I'll cover AmiTube (including 
  setting up your own transcode server) in a later issue.

  To download and transcode The Amiga Show, you will need:

  * A Linux machine, or a Windows machine running WSL (Windows Subsystem 
  for Linux)
  * FFMpeg (usually available as a package on Linux)
  * AGAConv - https://mschordan.github.io/amiga/agaconv.html
  * AGABlaster - https://mschordan.github.io/amiga/agablaster.html
  * YT-DLP - https://github.com/yt-dlp/yt-dlp
  * Access to YouTube to download The Amiga Show - 
  https://www.youtube.com/@theamigashow9506

  ## Getting The Video

  Available at https://github.com/yt-dlp/yt-dlp this tool is a swiss-army 
  knife for downloading streamable content. Not only YouTube is supported. 
  Yt-dlp can download from most video sites, sometimes with a bit of 
  finagling. Yt-dlp also supports tools like Sponsorblock, which removes 
  sponsor segments and ads. It also has support for geo-verification 
  bypasses and subtitles.

  You can install yt-dlp from binaries, pip or via your system. I'm using a 
  Linux-based system for getting and converting the video, but many of 
  these steps will work with no more than minor changes on a Mac or Windows 
  machine. I'm testing Episode 8 of The Amiga Show, available here: 
  https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=bWI-s_lHtjs

  YouTube supplies videos in different formats and resolutions. We'll test 
  AGABlaster in 320x240 resolution lores video. We'll download a 640x480 
  version with yt-dlp. Although it's possible to download 320x240 from 
  YouTube, compression artefacts on lower-resolution YouTube videos are far 
  more apparent. The command to download the 640x480 version of this video 
  in h264 with an mp4a audio track is:

  ```
  yt-dlp -f "bv*[height=480][vcodec~='^((he|a)vc|h26[45])']+ba[ext=m4a]" https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=bWI-s_lHtjs -o TAS08.mp4
  ```

  The cryptic -f value tells yt-dlp to download the best video with a 
  vertical resolution of 480p, a h264 or h265 video codec, along with the 
  best quality m4a audio stream. With a bit more work we can tell yt-dlp to 
  download the entire channel, which will come in helpful later:

  ```
  yt-dlp -f "bv*[height=480][vcodec~='^((he|a)vc|h26[45])']+ba[ext=m4a]" --download-archive tasvids.txt https://www.youtube.com/channel/UC-2a5umZHO7lyt8pcPcbdnQ -o '%(channel)s/%(title)s.%(ext)s' --restrict-filenames
  ```

  This uses the same format trick as before but downloads the channel's 
  videos to a directory named after the channel, using the title as the 
  filename. A list of downloaded videos is kept in the file tasvids.txt 
  stopping yt-dlp from downloading the same video twice when next run. A 
  script could run nightly to check for new episodes and download them 
  ready for processing and transfer. So far, so good. But how can we watch 
  the results on an A1200? We'll need to convert the video to CDXL format 
  with AGAConv.

  ## AGAConv

  Markus Schordan's AGAConv runs mainly under Linux, but Windows users can 
  use the Microsoft Ubuntu App to run AGAConv. The documentation at 
  https://mschordan.github.io/amiga/agaconv.html details how to download 
  and install the software.

  Once you have agaconv set up in the same directory as your downloaded 
  video, you're ready to start converting. There are a lot of options, and 
  a lot of choices depend on your setup. If you've ever played games like 
  Alien Breed 3D II and have switched between window sizes, pixel sizes and 
  floor and ceilings to optimize gameplay, this will feel familiar.

  The three main factors governing playback are:

  1. Transfer speed (disk bandwidth).
  2. File size and available space.
  3. Hardware configuration (CPU power, bus speed and chipset)

  Of the above, transfer speed is the most important. You're just not going 
  to transfer 640x480 Ham8 at 25 frames per second across a single-speed 
  CD-ROM, Zip disk or Zorro II SCSI Interface to a spinning disk. On the 
  one hand, my Amiga 4000 with FastATA and an 060 can comfortably play 
  320x240 Ham8 at 30 fps in stereo all day long. My CDTV barely manages 12 
  fps at 160x120off the CD-ROM drive.

  CDXL was designed for the CDTV, with a 68000 CPU. Latency and bandwidth 
  are more important than CPU power. Even my CDTV can decode CDXL at around 
  160x120 and a reasonable (for the time) frame rate. Storage and bandwidth 
  will dominate resolution, frame rate, colour depth and audio 
  configurations.

  The good news is that an AGA Amiga with reasonably fast storage can 
  deliver better than VCD quality in many cases. If your drive bandwidth is 
  slow, try reducing frame rate., resolution and switching to mono. 
  Unfortunately I don't have a CD32 to test with, but I suspect that 
  320x240 at around 10fps may be possible from CD. If you have a CD32 and 
  are happy to play around, send your results to the editor and we'll 
  include them in a future issue.

  Another point on bandwidth before we move on. If you're a A1200 owner 
  with fast ram and a stock 020, expect around 20FPS for 320x180 with 
  22050hz mono on internal IDE with a fast Compact Flash card. If you have 
  an 030/50 you should expect better results, especially if your turbo card 
  has a fast IDE interface.

  I cut a short 10 second clip from the episode 8 title screen 
  (3-13 seconds in) to test different AGA conversions. I used 22050hz 
  stereo audio (as the original audio was 44100hz) for my tests, running 
  ham8 and aga8 conversions at 30, 20, and 15 fps with the following 
  results (size in bytes, and filename):

  * AGA8, 30 FPS - 23242K 
  * HAM8, 30 FPS - 23073K
  * AGA8, 20 FPS - 15665K
  * HAM8, 20 FPS - 15552K
  * AGA8, 15 FPS - 11798K
  * HAM8, 15 FPS - 11714K

  The 256 colour AGA8 videos are larger than the HAM8 videos due to HAM 
  effectively acting as a kind of frame compression. The original MP4 video 
  is 126K, but that would never play on a stock Amiga 1200. Playing from 
  RAM disk is also typically faster than hard disk (especially for on-board 
  accelerated RAM), but obviously limits file size. To create a 10 second 
  clip for testing, I used the following command:

  ```
  ffmpeg -i The_Amiga_Show/The_Amiga_Show_Episode_08_-_May_86.mp4 -ss 00:00:03 -to 00:00:13 -c:v copy -c:a copy TAS08testclip.mp4
  ```

  Using a test clip is a great way to test different encoding strategies. 
  Video with little movement works better at lower FPS, while music videos 
  might support higher quality audio at lower resolutions.


  The command line I used to generate the HAM8 video was:

  ```
  ./agaconv "TAS08testclip.mp4" tas08_h8_320_30_s_22050.cdxl --color-mode=ham8 --audio-mode=stereo --frequency=22050 --fps=30 --width=320 --max-fps=30
  ```

  The first argument is the clip generated above. The second file is the 
  filename. As I made *a lot* of test files, I added the colours, 
  horizontal resolution, frames per second, whether it was stereo ("s") or 
  mono ("m"), and the sample rate in hertz to the filename. Most of the 
  remaining arguments are self-explanatory. Frequency refers to audio 
  sample rate, fps is frame-rate in frames per second and width sets the 
  width (as we're resizing a 640x480 video). The max-fps setting specifies 
  a max frame rate. It's not necessary but I added it anyway.

  ## AGABlaster

  Playing back the clips requires AGABlaster, available from 
  http://mschordan.github.io/amiga/agablaster.html - extract the archive 
  and copy the version for your CPU into your C: drawer and you're good to 
  go. Use the following command from the Amiga shell to play a video:

  ```
  agablaster filename.cdxl
  ```

  You should be able to create a file association so that CDXL files are 
  played by AGABlaster when double-clicked. The exact method varies with 
  AmigaOS versions but associations should be documented in your Workbench 
  manual. If you run agablaster from a shell with the keyword "STATS" 
  you'll see a report at the end of the video. This contains information 
  including the actual calculated fps vs encoded fps (in parentheses), 
  audio frame buffer delays (AFB) and video frame buffer delays (VFB). This 
  is helpful to spot where things fail when optimizing videos.

  You can seek forwards and backwards by 10 seconds using the left and 
  right keys. Use up and down to increase or decrease volume, space to 
  pause and M to mute or unmute audio. Backspace restarts the video, while 
  escape or the left mouse button quits agablaster. There's also a cute 
  copper effect that splits the screen into 4 or 16 windows with F2 or F3. 
  Press F1 to return back to a normal screen.

  ## Converting Bigger Videos

  By now you should've understood:

  1. How to download a video from YouTube
  2. How to extract a small clip
  3. How to encode this for playback on an Amiga
  4. How to play it back on an Amiga

  Now you know how to determine practical frame rates, resolutions and 
  expected video sizes (1-2mb per second for 320x240 at frame rates between 
  15 and 30 FPS), it's time to look at a bigger video. Different Amiga OS 
  versions come with different file restrictions. The most common 
  restriction is the 4.3Gb partition limit, closely followed by the 2Gb 
  file limit for some filesystems. Expect to burn through 1Gb every 500 
  seconds at 22050 and 30fps. To work around this, we can split our episode 
  of The Amiga Show and play the segments in agablaster.

  To start with, lets use ffprobe to determine the length of our episode:

  ```
  ffprobe TAS08.mp4
  ```

  In the results I saw the text *Duration: 00:27:32.45*. So that's roughly 
  27 minutes and 33 seconds or 1653 seconds. Using the example above for 
  Ham8 video:

  * HAM8, 30 FPS: 1653 Seconds * 2.3 Mb/Sec = 3801.9Mb
  * HAM8, 20 FPS: 1653 * 1.55 Mb/Sec = 2562.15Mb
  * HAM8, 15 FPS: 1653 * 1.17 Mb/Sec = 1934.01Mb

  We could encode the episode at 15 FPS to fit the entire episode under the 
  Amiga's native 2gb file limit. Another alternative is to use a 
  non-standard filesystem supporting larger files, such as PFS3 or FAT95. 
  An excellent guide to different Amiga filesystems and their limits can be 
  found here: https://eab.abime.net/showthread.php?t=61666

  If you use an editor such as the superb Kdenlive 
  (https://kdenlive.org/en/), you can cut the episode into parts up to 10 
  minute clips. The encoded videos will come in under the native file size 
  limit. When playing in AGABlaster there will be a slight gap between one 
  video ending and starting. It's best to cut at quiet parts, ideally on a 
  solid or black screen.

  If you don't mind the odd potential pause while videos change over, the 
  following command will automagically split the episode into 3 roughly 
  equal sized chunks of 9 minute and 10 seconds.

  ```
  mkdir -p tmp
  ffmpeg -i The_Amiga_Show_Episode_08_-_May_86.mp4 -c copy -map 0 -segment_time 00:09:10.0 -f segment -reset_timestamps 1 tmp/tase08_%03d.mp4
  ```

  The above will create 3 files - tas08_000.mp4, tas08_001.mp4, and 
  tas08_003.mp4 in a tmp/ folder. AGAConv can turn these into separate cdxl 
  files using the following command:

  ```
  for i in tmp/*.mp4; do f=`basename "${i}" .mp4` ; ./agaconv "${i}" "tmp/${f}_h8_30.cdxl" --color-mode=ham8 --audio-mode=stereo --frequency=22050 --fps=30 --width=320 --max-fps=30 ; done
  ```

  Each of the files should come in around 1.3Gb in size. Copy them over to 
  your Amiga and you'll be good to go.

  ## Getting More From AGAConv/AGABlaster

  Use short clips for lower transcode time while testing. This will make 
  optimization so much easier. You can always do a final encode once you're 
  happy with the results. When testing playback under emulation be aware
  that most Amiga emulators don't accurately emulate drive access speeds. 
  Expect significantly higher performance on emulated systems than the real 
  thing.

  Although the fastest transfer rate usually wins, it's worth testing 
  different mediums and filesystems. My A4000 can run full speed, full 
  320x240 video with full stereo 22050hz on my FastATA-powered Compact 
  Flash card. My DVD-ROM drive can still play the same videos at 17 FPS 
  from the A4000's internal IDE interface. If you don't have UDF support 
  via CacheCDFS or AsimCDFS, try  
  http://aminet.net/package/disk/misc/DVD-RAM from Aminet. I get a 
  rock-solid 30 FPS via FAT32-formatted USB drives, but I get constant 
  glitches (possibly due to DMA complexities with my setup). I've also 
  experienced significantly better playback performance with PFS than on 
  FFS. PFS can be found on Aminet at 
  https://aminet.net/package/disk/misc/pfs3aio but this YouTube video might 
  also be useful if you're setting it up on a new drive: 
  https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=CytF5LNzpqE

  Audio seems to significantly impact playback quality, especially on less 
  capable systems. If playback is stuttering or sounds like it's time-
  stretching, try using mono or a lower frame rate. Most YouTube video is 
  encoded at 44.1 Khz, so encoding audio at 22050 or 11025 should avoid 
  aliasing effects you might experience at other frequency settings.

  Hopefully by now you should be ready to watch The Amiga Show as it should 
  be seen... on your Amiga! Don't forget, yt-dlp can download way more than 
  just YouTube. The full list of supported sites can be found here: 
  https://github.com/yt-dlp/yt-dlp/blob/master/supportedsites.md - You can 
  download from BBC iPlayer, Bandcamp, Disney and more! In my next article 
  I'll walk through optimizing video for OCS/ECS systems and playback on 
  1.3 machines like the CDTV.

  
@endnode

@node lightwave101 "LightWave 101 - Creating A Starfield"
@toc guides
============================================================================
 	          @{b}LightWave 101 - Part 7@{ub} - by: @{"Timo Paul" link timopaul}
============================================================================

  ##Starfield

  As we move into winter and say goodbye to Autumn, the night skies become 
  a feast for the eyes with stars and stellar views. However if you live
  in an area with cloudy skies then you are out out luck, so if you can't
  see the stars above how about making our own star view?

  ##Particles
 
  For this tutorial we are going to be spending most of our time in the
  modeler using particles, or single-point polygons. A characteristic of 
  this polygon is that it will render the same size no matter how far it 
  is from from the camera. 

  With LightWave 3.5 it became possible to choose the rendered screen 
  size of particles and lines:
 
  Small, Medium or Large. 

  Essentially this means a single particle can rendered at one pixel, 
  3x3 pixels or 5x5 pixel arrays. Why this is important you will find out 
  later on.

  With that out of the way, let's get down to the business of making our
  star field. I presume you are in the Modeler, if not, go there now. In
  the modeler select New or press 'N' (the key presses will be capital
  and lowercase sensitive, so (N = shift + N key) and (n = N key) and 
  click on 'OK'. This time we are going to use one of the macros that 
  come with LightWave, click on 'Macro' and find "Point Distributions".
  When the dialogue box pops up enter "10,000" into the 'Number of points'
  box, set 'Falloff Towards' to "Center" and 'Density Distribution' to
  "Constant", you can leave the rest as is. Click on 'OK' to start creating
  your star field, it will take some time depending on your processor.

  ##Naming Your Starfield

  Once LightWave has finished calculating the particles you will see 
  something that looks akin to a cotton ball. This is the beginning of our
  starfield. Next we need to select all the polygon surfaces, the easiest
  way to do this is to go into 'Polygon selection mode' by pressing the
  (spacebar) and rename the surface to 'Stars 1', renaming can be done in 
  the 'Polygon' menu, under the 'Transform' heading. Click on the 'Surface'
  button and type in 'Stars 1' or much easier, press (q). Save this object
  with a name of 'Stars1.10k' i.e. it is our first Stars object and it is
  made up on 10,000 points. 

  Now we need to grow our starfield and this will be done by pressing (c)
  to copy the particles, if you wish to use the mouse the same actions can
  be done with the 'Copy' button at the bottom on of the screen. Next go to
  layer 2, this can be found at the top right of the screen where there are
  20 little square buttons. Currently the button on the far left is 
  selected as indicated by the yellow colour. Click on the box next to it 
  on left and paste the copied starfield by pressing either (v) or clicking
  on 'Paste' at the bottom of the screen. You should see your object now
  duplicated on the screen. If we were to stack the two objects the would
  overlap each other and that would be not be of much help in creating our
  starfield, what we need to do is add some randomness and this is achieved
  via jitter. To do this you can either press (J) or go to the 'Tools' menu
  and select 'Jitter' under the 'Points' heading. Our radius is only 1m so
  we can set the 'Radius' X, Y and Z to '0.1m' which is (5-10 percent of 
  the radius). When finished rename the surface using the key (q) to 
  'Stars2' and save the object out as 'Stars2.10k'. Repeat this process 
  three more times for the first five layers.

  ##The Last Two

  Now that you have created five starfields each one that has been jittered
  and copied to the five first layers we will work on the last two. For our
  sixth field, go to layer six, create a new starfield using the same 
  "Point Distributions" macro but this time enter 5,000 for the particles
  with the same previous settings. Rename the surface to 'Stars 6', and 
  save out the object as 'Stars6.5k'. Finally we can work on our last star
  field, just like before go to layer seven, create another starfield with
  the same macro but this time with 1,000 particles, rename the surface to
  'Stars 7' and save it out as 'Stars7.1k'.
 
  So that is it for this issue, next time we will look at how to bring your
  starfield into the Layout program, set up the camera and render your star
  scene, we might even dip a little into animation. Good luck and have a
  wonderful winter holidays, keep rendering and see you in the February 
  2023 issue!      

@endnode  

@node brilliance101 "Brilliance 101 - Reflections"
@toc guides
============================================================================
 	          @{b}Brilliance 101 Part 7@{ub} - by: @{"Timo Paul" link timopaul}
============================================================================

  ##Mirror, mirror ... 

  Reflections, a great effect that looks amazing when used in a 3D 
  rendering package but how do we create a convincing and easy effect in
  a 2D paint package. Well Brilliance has you covered here with two tools.
  First off we will be using TrueBrilliace since the larger pallete helps
  in creating a much more realistic effect plus we can bring in other 
  images and there will be no need to remap the colours since you have the
  full 24Bit pallete at your disposal.

  ##Going back

  If you remember in our first tutorial we created a checkered marble 
  texture, if you still have that go grab it and create a brush from it.
  Now we have the marble texture as a brush, let's set the perspective of
  the brush, this time however we are going to set it quite low. Go to the
  'Tweening' menu and click on 'Adjust', now we will adjust the 'XY' Pos
  to near the bottom of the screen. Next adjust the 'X' Rot so you have a
  nice perspective, for my example image I used a value of 79. Once you
  have finished the 'X' Rot move the 'XY' Pos to the lower part of the 
  screen, if possible have the bottom just about disappearing into from
  view. When you are finished, click on 'Use'. Now we can fill in the 
  perspective, if you remember from before use 'Draw Mode' and 
  'Perspective', once you have filled in your screen you should have a
  realistic looking perspective with the impression you are standing.

  ##Clouds, so many clouds ...    
 
  In the last issue we reviewed Clouds AGA, well now is the time to use it.
  Open the Clouds AGA (Or download it if you have not) create a quick image
  of a cloud, it does not have to be too big but if you have the time, an
  image size of 400 x 400 would be suitable.

  Okay, I presume you have rendered your clouds and saved it as an image by
  now. Close Clouds AGA and go back to TrueBrilliance, we currently have 
  our marble floor, for the next part we need to use a buffer screen and 
  this can be done by pressing the 'J' key, it will take you to another
  screen. If you press the space bar you can see , in the 'Buffer' tool bar
  the two spare screens available, it is possible to add more buffers by
  clicking on 'Add' but for the moment we are going to use two, using
  multiple buffers will be for another guide.

  You should have the clouds image now loaded into your buffer screen, so
  cut out as large a brush as possible, then press the 'J' key switch back
  to your working image or the space bar to bring up the buffer toolbar and 
  click on the far left side of the slider to get back to your image. Don't 
  worry if you brush colours look the same, give it a moment for 
  TrueBrilliance to remap the colours. Now we will go back to the 
  'Tweening' menu but for this instance we will be creating the sky all we
  need to do is change the 'XY' Pos to the upper part of the screen, click 
  and drag it to the top of you can use the same values in my example image
  which are 0 and -256, click on 'Use' and then use the perspective tool to
  fill in the top half of the screen. Now you should have a bottom and top
  perspective of a marble floor and blue sky and clouds. If you feel your
  marble floor is a bit dark you can use the 'Brighten' in 'Draw Mode' to
  make the marble a bit brigher, this can be done by simply drawing a white
  filled rectangle over the entire marble floor, making sure 'Draw Mode' is
  activated and 'Brighten' is selected.

  ##Reflecting Our Clouds

  Now it is time to reflect our clouds and to do that we will be using the 
  same cloud brush that we used to make the sky. Also we will go back to 
  the 'Tweening' menu and use the same settings or as near as possible as 
  the marble flooring. Once you have done that we will go to 'Draw Mode'
  menu and choose perspective.  Before you draw anything you need to also
  go to the 'Trasparent' tool and set your transparency level, for my image
  I chose 19% as a good balance between the marble floor and reflection of
  the sky, but you it pays off to have a play around. Instead of using the
  fill bucket this time we are going to use a filled rectangle, draw a
  rectangle covering the entire marble floor. Slowly you will see the image
  crawl down with a transparent and perspective blue sky.

  Hopefully by now you have an image with a reflected sky on the perspective
  marble floor. If you want to add something more you can grab a brush of
  the sky and floor, then choose 'Filled Eclipse', from the 'Draw Mode'
  menu select 'Shape' and you can draw a globe that is reflecting both the
  sky and floor. If you want to reflect the globe on the floor, then I
  recommend using the buffer screen to draw out the shape filled globe,
  grab it as a brush and the flip it with the 'Brush Distort' tool. Before
  pressing down the brush make sure to adjust the 'Transparency' for a more
  realistic reflective effect.

  Well that is the last guide for this year, I hope you have enjoyed the
  our exploration of Brilliance and look forward to continuing the series
  in 2023. Have a wonderful winter holidays and see you in 2023!
                                                   
@endnode           		   

@node amigastorage "Amiga A1200 Storage Solution"
@toc guides
============================================================================
               @{b}Amiga A1200 Storage Solution@{ub} - by: @{"Timo Paul" link timopaul}
============================================================================

  ##Tiny Houses

  We all want to display our Amigas and have easy access to them, however
  for those of us living in smaller domiciles having, our beloved Amigas
  available all the time is not always an option. 
  
  If you have ever lived in Japan, you will know that the available space 
  in apartments and houses can be quite limited. With some of the newer
  houses the floor space has increased but the average person lives in a
  considerably smaller space than those in the United States or Europe. As
  such it is common for family members to share a desk or have the desk in
  a communal area. This can cause some issues for Amiga users, however 
  there is an option for A500, A600 and A1200 users. While only one brand
  of product is used is this guide there are others, the main points to
  take away from this guide are the dimensions.

  ##Sanwa Keyboard Tray

  The keyboard tray was ordered from Amazon Japan, and was delivered by 
  Sanwa Direct, not from the Amazon. It comes in a large and heavy 
  cardboard box. When opened the tray is already put together.
 
  All you need to do is make space on your desk and tighten the bolts. My 
  desk has a thickness of 1.5cm, with the keyboard tray attached this gives 
  me a clearance of 8cm, perfectly fine for an A1200 that sits at 6.5cm.

  The keyboard tray's dimensions are 51cm wide and 29.6cm deep, this fits
  the A1200 perfectly allowing the Amiga to sit comfortably and not hang 
  over the edge. You will not be able to use a mouse though on the tray, it
  will have to be used on your desk which means leaning over every so 
  slightly to reach it. Including the tray height you are looking at a 
  total height of 12.8cm so using a lower chair will make it a more 
  comfortable typing experience.

  ##Availability
  
  As the moment it is only available to Japanese households from Amazon 
  Japan, however as it is being sent directly from Sanwa Direct it is worth
  contacting them about international shipping. Japan Post offers some 
  great rates when items are shipped by Surface mail (3 months average) and
  if you suggest this to Sanwa they will most likely be happy to oblidge
  you.

  When I checked on Amazon.com there is another keyboard tray that looks 
  almost the same, the 'Huanuo Keyboard Tray 27" Large Size', this is 
  easily available in the United States and UK.

  ##Final Thoughts

  While having our Amiga on the desk at all times would be ideal, some of 
  us are not lucky enough to have the space or understanding spouses so we 
  need to keep our Amiga hidden. Having to take out the Amiga and plug in 
  the cables each time you want to use your Amiga is not an ideal 
  situation. The Sanwa keyboard tray is a solid and effective way of 
  stowing away your Amiga when not is use and easy to slide out when you 
  do. It has given me my limited desk space back and looks great when slid
  out. When it is under the desk my wife thankfully forgets its there. 

  If you want to hide your Amiga away but have easy access to it then 
  using a keyboard tray is an effective solution.
  
  While this is just one product there are other keyboard trays available, 
  try to find one that has the following dimensions:

      * 10cm clearance between keyboard tray and the bottom of the desk.
      * At least 51cm wide.
      * At least 29.5cm deep.
      * Total height (including keyboard tray thickness) of 12.8cm.

  If you find one that is easily available in your country then contact us
  so we can add the information to the magazine.     

@endnode               

