============================================================================
    @{b}The birth of the Amiga-News.de Advent Calendar@{ub} - by: @{"Daniel Reimann" link danielreimann}
============================================================================

  What happens when Corona, the Amiga37 and the anticipation of the Advent 
  season come together? Exactly, the idea for the Amiga-News.de Advent 
  calendar :)
  After two years of successfully fending off Corona, it finally hit me at 
  the end of September. The temptation was obvious to condemn the world 
  and everything. After a short while, however, I decided to make 
  something positive out of it: as bad as I felt, I wanted to use the 
  forced time at home to start planning a virtual Advent calendar.

  As a child, I loved Advent - and in my mid-40s, I still do ;) Obligatory 
  equipment was always an Advent calendar. The Amiga37 was about to open 
  and when I felt the anticipation for this event through our extensive 
  reporting in advance, I thought: why not bring Amiga and Advent calendar 
  together? And since reading out stories has always been part of Advent, 
  the idea was born to create an Amiga Advent calendar with anecdotes from 
  developers, programmers, publishers and creative people and to give them 
  a small stage to introduce themselves at the same time. No sooner said 
  than done: a list of potential candidates was quickly compiled and one 
  mail after the other was sent out.
  I was totally surprised by the positive feedback: actually everyone who 
  thought being able to write a story wanted to take part.

  However, I reached my limits when I tried to find a graphic designer to 
  create the announcement: unfortunately, they were all booked up!
  Making a virtue out of necessity, I now dared to take on this task 
  myself and am satisfied with the result - against the background of my 
  very limited skills: a picture of the local Christmas market (which was 
  under construction at this time) was taken and placed as background 
  picture for a window in AmigaOS 4, drawers were created and the whole 
  thing saved. Using paint.net a headline and the initials of the 
  participants (as a little puzzle) were added. Finished:

  https://www.amiga-news.de/en/news/AN-2022-11-00129-EN.html

  And so our calendar has been running since 1 December and has not only 
  provided us with amusing and beautiful anecdotes, but also awakened many 
  memories. At the same time, the calendar offers a small summary of 
  previous and current projects for the respective patron and thus an 
  appreciation of all those who make an effort for the Amiga. Because 
  without them there would be nothing to report, without them, we would 
  only live in the past. But no, even in the year 2022 software and 
  hardware for the Amiga is being developed. Great.
  
  We hope you enjoy the rest of the stories. It's worthwhile to stop by! 
  And the 24th of December, we promise, will be special...;)

@endnode

@node ivanalookback "A Look Back At 2022"
@toc articles
============================================================================
	     @{b}A Look Back At 2022@{ub} - by: @{"Ivan Sorensen" link ivansorensen}
============================================================================
  
  #A Look Back ...
  
  The year is coming to a close and so it is time to reflect. 

  For a system that has not been sold since Amiga Technologies, the Amiga 
  is quite alive these days. It seems that every month brings some piece of 
  new kit to expand your system or make it ever more adaptable to current 
  technology. 

  What is interesting is that it seems no machines are being left behind: 
  For a while it was mainly the 1200 and the big box machines that were 
  getting targeted but we have seen new kit aimed specifically at the 500 
  and 600 as well.

  Retro computing is a bit of an odd market place in that so much is 
  kit-bashed or made to small production runs and the availability of an 
  item in theory is no guarantee that it can actually be purchased when you 
  go to look for it later. While I wholeheartedly believe Amiga does not 
  have to be a multi-thousand dollar hobby, you are often best advised to 
  buy things you really want when they are available, as they will rarely 
  remain so.

  On the software side the focus is usually mostly on games. I have 
  recently embarked on a (probably impossible) quest to play every Amiga 
  game ever released, which meant compiling a list of said games. One thing 
  I noticed is that the number of new Amiga titles have steadily been 
  increasing since 2012/2013 or so and while some new games are mainly tech 
  demos, many are quite awesome original creations as well as ports of 
  classics from other systems.
  
  In fact the wave of new releases was part of why I ended up opting to 
  replace my floppy disk drive with a Gotek, since so many of them are 
  available on ADF.

  Bridging the gap between hardware and software we are also now living in 
  a world where actual Amiga OS updates have been happening and seems to 
  continue to do so. Would anyone have guessed that 10 years ago? 
  I am not on board the 3.2 train yet, since I am pretty in love with my 
  ClassicWB setup but every day the interest increases. Plus I am big on 
  'digital minimalism' lately so going back to basics a little sounds like 
  a good exercise. 

  On a personal level, this was also a good year for Amiga: 
  My system is now set up in the living room and every night I take an hour 
  or so to play a couple games, check out a demo or listen to some mods. I 
  have been looking at ways to spend less time on the internet and the 
  Amiga is a nice way of doing so, especially since there was so much 
  content I never experienced at the time. I think I saw maybe five demos 
  at the time, so being able to access the huge library of demos and watch 
  them now is pretty fun.

  To me collecting is only ever a side hobby (I own 7 game boxes and a few 
  manuals for the Amiga). The purpose of the system is to use it and every 
  purchase I make for it is aimed towards that goal. 

  In conclusion it has been a strong year for the Amiga and I look forward 
  to seeing what crazy, innovative and groundbreaking things people come up 
  with in the new year. 

@endnode

@node usmagazines "From Across The Pond: US Amiga Magazines"
@toc articles
============================================================================
	     @{b}From Across The Pond: US Amiga Magazines@{ub} - by: @{"Timo Paul" link timopaul}
============================================================================

  Magazines played a large part in the Amiga's life, we all have memories
  of going to the newsagents/bookstore to see if the latest issue of our
  favourite magazine was out. The UK in particular is well known for 
  having had many Amiga magazines; Amiga Format, CU Amiga, The One, Amiga
  Power, Amiga User International, Amiga Computing, Amiga Shopper, and
  probably more, that alone is seven that I could list off the top of
  my head. The US howver is not recognised as having had many Amiga 
  magazines, the most famous being Amiga World and Amazing Computing 
  Amiga. There were many more though early in the life of the Amiga 
  published in the US. Amigo Times, Amiga Resource, Transactor, Comodore 
  Magazine, Amiga Plus, Ahoy Amiga, AX, Graf/X, Amiga Informer, .info and 
  Amiga Sentry. That takes us up to 13 different magazines, if we add in 
  the magazines dedicated to the VideoToaster such as Video Toaster User,
  and LightWave Pro, it takes us up to 15 magazines! Having lived in the
  UK I would have never imagined there were 15 different Amiga magazines
  of sorts, it just goes to show how the US Amiga market was viewed 
  differently from across the pond.

  That being said, my experience with the Amiga started in the US, we 
  were living in Pennslyvania during the release of the A500 and as 
  luck would have it our family purchased an A500 with Commodore monitor.
  Along with the Amiga I was also introduced to the world of Amiga
  magazines, in our area there were only two Amiga magazines easily 
  available in the bookstore, video game shop or camera/video stores, yes
  it is a bit different than the UK. My goto magazines were Amiga World
  and Amazing Computing Amiga, of the two I preferred Amazing Computing a
  bit more as it concentrated more on the creative uses of the Amiga. That
  does not mean Amiga World did not have enough creative articles, in fact
  far from it, but I preferred the writing style and attitude of Amazing
  Computing. 

  In regards to the differences between the US magazines, I found the size
  to be immmediatly noticable, the UK magazines come in at the typical A4
  size but the US magazine size is a bit shorter. The page count did not
  go much above 100 pages, the UK magazines definitely being thicker and
  bigger. I find that I prefer the former format though more as it is a bit 
  easier to hold and fits easier into a bag.

  Amiga World and Amazing Computing Amiga were both there at the beginning
  of the Amiga's life with Amiga World's and Amazing Computing Amiga's 
  first issues coming out in 1985. Amiga World was published by TechMedia 
  Publishing in New Hampshire, a one year subscription fee was USD 29.97
  and for the rest of the world USD 84.97 Airmail. It was stated at one
  point in the magazine that they had 100,000 subscribers. Amazing 
  Computing Amiga was published by PIM Publications Inc. in Massachusetts, 
  a one year subscription was USD 29.95 and outside the US USD 49.97 via 
  Surface. It is interesting seeing how much cheaper the subscriptions were 
  for the US magazines compared to the UK magazines, although it should be
  noted AW and AC did not come with any cover disks.

  Looking back at an issue of Amiga World it is interesting to see how much
  more text there is verses the bright and visual Amiga Format/CU Amiga.
  The UK magazines seemed to want to assualt your eyes with large full 
  colour images, Amiga World and Amazing Computing were a bit more 
  restrained in their use of imagery. Amazing Computing however did have
  more images and colour than Amiga World, they had a tendancy to use half
  the page for images which AW seemed to avoid.

  When reading Amiga World, it feels very much like a newspaper, there is
  a lot of text, you can go several pages at a time without a photo or
  image. In in a way it makes it feel like a product aimed at the mature 
  reader, the UK magazines at times felt like they were for the teenagers
  who had an attention span of 30 seconds. While there was a little more
  colour and imagery to Amazing Computing it still did not have the large
  photos and images of the UK magazines, again it also felt like a magazine 
  targeting the older audiences. Thinking about it now, the Amiga was 
  largely used as a game machine in the UK so the general use Amiga 
  magazines had to take that into consideration.

  The nature of the articles was another area of difference, if you wanted
  to read game reviews there were just 3-4 pages and contained just a 
  paragraph or two, and maybe one photo for the whole page. Amazing 
  Computing had a little more colour and images but it was also mostly 
  columns of text when it came to game reviews.

  While these two magazines may not have not put in the same effort into
  reviewing games as their cousins across the pond, when it came to doing
  tutorials and reviews you could guarantee on them having some of the best
  articles. In fact most of what I learnt about the Amiga was from AW and
  AC, these magazines were made to support your creative use of the Amiga
  and they were at the top of their game with video production, 3D 
  rendering, music production, graphics techniques to building the most
  powerful Amiga possible. Reading the UK magazines made me think the big
  box Amigas were interesting but it was when reading the US magazines that
  I decided to upgrade to an A3000 with a Picasso II card, their coverage 
  of the bigbox Amigas was far greater, demonstrating how to create a more
  capable Amiga. One other aspect of Amiga World that I liked was the 
  'Your Turn' that would crop up in reviews, these were little boxes that
  had a sort review of the product written by the readers. It was a nice
  way to balance the reviews giving your a broader idea of the product.

  Amazing Computing Amiga delved a bit deeper into tutorials having full
  programming guides, graphics and other tutorials on how to improve the
  look of your Workbench. The magazine tailored to the user who likes to
  tinker around with their Amiga and try to get the most out of the 
  software and hardware. If you needed to find some help on how to do 
  some graphic trick or rendering technique then your best chance would be
  in Amazing Compututing Amiga. Amiga World in a way was the Amiga Format 
  for the US market and Amazing Computing Amiga was the CU Amiga 
  equivalent. Both magazines though came out several years before the UK 
  publications so it should be the otherway round.
 
  When I moved back to the UK I continued a subscription to Amiga World and
  Amazing Computing Amiga. It was always exciting to see the white envelope
  with the US postal stamp come through the mail slot. Even with all the
  choices of UK Amiga magazines available to me in the shops I kept up with
  Amiga World until its last issue in 1994 and Amazing Computing until 1999
  when it too closed. It was a very sad day for me when I received my last
  issue of Amazing Computing Amiga, more than any other Amiga magazines, 
  these two magazines helped shape and direct my Amiga adventures and I 
  often go back to my old issues to read up something I had forgotten about 
  or learn something new.
                         
  If you are new to the Amiga or have been around for a long time and have 
  not read Amiga World or Amazing Computing Amiga, I highly recommend 
  having a look. It is easy to download an issue from the Internet Archive
  sites or if you are willing to spend some cash buy back issues from 
  places such as eBay. There is software and hardware that I have not seen
  reviewed in UK magazines and even some games that seemed to not have been
  written about in British magazines. But it is the tutorials and guides on
  software such as Brilliance, LightWave and ImageFX that make the issues
  still stand out all these years later.

  This was just my experience of Amiga magazines, how about you, what 
  memories or experiences do you have? Write in to WhatIFF? and we would
  love to hear about your experiences. We can be contacted at:
  
  			submissions@whatiff.info      
          
@endnode 

@node ldcomputer
@toc articles
============================================================================
    		@{b}Amiga - The First LD Computer@{ub} - by: @{"Timo Paul" link timopaul}
============================================================================

  "The first LD computer?!", you are thinking, "What does he mean?", well
  let me clear some things up first, when I say LD I mean Learning 
  Difficulty. You may know me as the editor of WhatIFF? but unfortunately
  that is not my full time job, though it can feel like it at times. My work 
  is with children who have learning difficulties, more specifically I am a
  dyslexia specialist. I go to schools and learners homes to help children
  who have dyslexia learn how to read and write. It is a job that is in
  some respects as far away from technology as possible since using paper
  and pen is a very important part of the job. The reason I decided to do
  a job like this is because I am also dyslexic, I had a tough time in
  school, my teachers orginally thought I was deaf, that is how severe my
  dyslexia was and still is, just ask my wife! It does not help that I have 
  an auditory processing disablilty on top of that. You are probably now
  thinking, "Hang on, if you have dyslexia, why are you writing a magazine?"
  
  A fair question, firstly I love the Amiga and secondly I enjoy pushing 
  myself and writing is still a hard job for me. But writing about the 
  Amiga makes it a bit easier, the Amiga is akin to taking novocain.
  
  Now that is out of the way, let's get back to the main topic of this
  article, why is the Amiga the first true LD friendly computer? To 
  understand why this is so we need to look at how we help dyslexic 
  learners. For most learning is done via rote (which is repeat many times
  until the student remembers) it is fine for most students, but for this 
  to work you have to be able to read and write without issue in the first
  place.

  If you are unable to read and write properly pretty much all learning in
  the school enviroment becomes very difficult, hence the reason dyslexia
  is considered a learning difficulty. It has been at times viewed as a 
  learning disability but disability means that something is not possible
  i.e. a person without legs can not walk, i.e. they are disabled. A child
  with dyslexia can learn, but they learn in a different way and that is
  why we call dyslexia a learning difficulty.

  When teaching a dyslexic learner we take it slowly, there is a lot of 
  repetition but the informatiton is presented in a variety of ways using 
  auditory, visual and physical techniques. Often moving the body, speaking
  and looking all together help the learner retain the new information. 

  Dyslexic learners respond better when they can see, hear and touch a 
  concept. This is where the Amiga comes in. Being the first home computer 
  that could offer real sound, animation and graphics along with the 
  physical input of the mouse as standard it became the first computer to 
  provide input for all the senses. We had a teacher who did not tire or 
  get angry that you made the same mistake the 20th time. We could hear and 
  see a concept, though the animation and auditory abilities of the Amiga.

  Whats more the Amiga could even read our text back to us, sure it was not 
  perfect but whatever we wrote it would not laugh at our mistakes but just 
  show us where the mistake was. For writing school reports this was a true
  game changer. The Amiga is often remembered as the first real multimedia 
  computer but it was also the first real computer that could give leaners
  with dyslexia an edge that they had never had before.

  I remember with fond memories using the spell checker and having my Amiga
  read me back what I had written. The educational software had sampled 
  sounds and animations and using the mouse gave me better hand and motor 
  control. It was a whole new world of learning that gave me not only the
  confidence to learn more but also to enjoy it. Eventually the Amiga's
  multimedia abilities started to affect my school work as well. For 
  example in music class we had to write a song and play it on an 
  instrument, I already was struggling trying to figure out how to play
  any instrument. So I was told I could use my Amiga, it was this pint that
  I encountered OctaMED and started my journey of tracking. The 4 channels
  and columns were so much easier than reading and writing music notes on 
  paper. It did not end there, already I had been playing around with 
  DPaint and when I brought in my Amiga to show my art teacher, I used the
  HAM mode. She was blown away and asked me to do a series of computer 
  images for class. I am here now because the Amiga could support my multi
  sensory teaching through it's multimedia capabilities.

  Now in my mid 40s I am able to read, write and spell with relative ease
  and enjoy reading greatly. I believe that this is in part thanks to my 
  Amiga for helping me get through school and for being one of my teachers.

  If you are still reading this, thank you for sticking with me on this 
  journey into the Amiga and dyslexia. It is thanks to the forward thinking 
  designers that the Amiga could support LD children in the 80s like no 
  other computer for over 10 years.
  
@endnode


