@node anthony "The Amiga Show's Anthony Interview"
@toc talkingamiga
============================================================================
	       @{b}Interview - Anthony (The Amiga Show)@{ub}
============================================================================

  Hello Anthony, thank you for agreeing to take the time to participate in 
  our interview.

  @{b}1. To start with can you tell us a little about yourself and your 
     background?@{ub}

  Hello! I'm Anthony and I've been into video and animation for a long as I 
  can remember. From the age of 6 I wanted to be a TV cameraman! Although 
  that didn't quite happen, my love of cameras remains and I did end up 
  working in Film and TV in Visual Effects, which I still do today.

  @{b}2. How did you get started with computers and the Amiga?@{ub}

  The first computer we had was a ZX Spectrum, which I absolutely loved; 
  played games on it, tried to write games on it (in basic, and not that 
  well). Eventually I saw images of the Amiga and I could not believe what 
  I was seeing, and eventually saved up enough money for an A500 (KS 1.3 
  had just arrived. My friend's machine was bought 2 months prior and came 
  with 1.2). The jump from the Speccy to the Amiga was incredible, I was 
  hooked! The graphics, sound, even the keyboard was such a step up.

  @{b}3. You are the creator of the YouTube video The Amiga Show, can you tell 
  us a little about the show and why you decided to create it?@{ub}

  Going back about 10 years or so, I saw there was a surge of people 
  streaming online. It coincided with my renewed interest in the Amiga, so 
  I had this idea that I could make a Saturday morning type show on the 
  Video Toaster; streaming it live from the Amiga. There could be Cartoons, 
  game reviews, some music, that kind of thing. But I realized that it 
  would take a certain personality type to pull this off and not really for 
  me. But I still thought streaming from the Toaster was a fun idea. 

  At this point I had no Amigas at all (having got rid of them in the mid 
  90's) never mind a Video Toaster. Slowly I started coming back to the 
  Amiga scene, pickup bits and pieces along the way until I had a 
  functional Toaster. By this point, I realised what I wanted to do was 
  document this wonderful machine and community, using the machine itself.

  The Amiga Show was born.

  @{b}4. Your show is quite unique in that you use a Video Toaster, which is 
  rarely seen outside the United States, how difficult was it to obtain one 
  in the UK?@{ub}

  It seemed an impossible dream when the Video Toaster appeared on the 
  front cover of Amiga Format. I had wanted one ever since!

  I ended up scouring eBay and found US sellers that were selling boards. 
  You're right though, running it in the UK can be fraught with difficulty 
  (being an NTSC product) particularly as I'm using an Amiga 2000. This 
  setup requires hardware modification to fit an NTSC oscillator to the 
  motherboard, as the Toaster requires very strict timings to run.

  It's also best to use it with 2mb of chip RAM, so that also need to be 
  sourced. The complication being a I needed to find a compatible Fat 
  Agnus! Oh boy, I'd forgotten these traumas :D.


  @{b}5. Which version of the Video Toaster did you purchase such as 2.0 or 
     Video Toaster 4000 and why?@{ub}

  I actually have both, although currently I'm using a 2.0 board, and 
  keeping the 4000 card as a backup. I would love to run the show from an 
  Amiga 4000 as some point, but that feels like a project for another time. 
  It means I lose some of the 4000 effects, but equally it gives the show 
  a more time appropriate appearance, which is part of the goal; to feel 
  like it's archive of a forgotten show.

  I also use a Flyer card with a bunch of SCSI to SD cards. This turns the 
  toaster into a non-linear editor and is very much the heart of the 
  production.

  @{b}6. What kind of any difficulties did you encounter setting it up, such 
     as PAL to NTSC conversion?@{ub}

  The is a HUGE part of the puzzle. I've struggled with multiple was of 
  doing it, each has benefits and drawbacks. My go-to solution is a Sony 
  1024G standards converter. This is a prosumer cross converter than can 
  take VGA/PAL/NTSC video (composite/s-video/RGB) and convert it to any of 
  those. It's is a real swiss-army knife! The output is a bit soft though; 
  it's a trade-off.

  The other way is to convert the video on a timeline on a Mac or PC, but 
  that can lead to long render times, and I feel it breaks the spirit of 
  the show.


  @{b}7. How did you find learning the software since there are a lot of 
     components to the VT system?@{ub}

  It definitely has complexity to it, but the real joy of the system is the 
  way it works together with each software module. The editor, paint system, 
  Lightwave and the caption generator all work together. It's really very 
  impressive, I'm still only scratching the surface.

  Fortunately, there are some amazing resources out there! YouTube has a 
  great number of companion and instructional VHSs and have been going 
  through those.

  Can I also add huge thanks to amigavideo.net. It has a great archive of 
  training videos for loads of Amiga titles. It's such a great resource, 
  there has never been a better time to dust of a copy of Vista Pro and 
  getting to work!

  @{b}8. Since the VT was not particularly well known outside the States, 
     where were you able to get advice and support from?@{ub}

  EAB has really been a great help. I had been following the on-going 
  trials from another board member and his experiences were invaluable. 
  There was also a dedicated cable that I need to make myself (gulp) but 
  eventually found a diagram and was reasonably straight-forward, even for 
  someone like me!

  @{b}9. Did you ever use the Video Toaster: The Desktop Video Magazine as a 
     resource for your channel? @{ub}

  I really should do, I imagine it's stuffed with tricks and ideas. That is 
  actually a great idea! Thankyou :D

  @{b}10. What has surprised you most about using the VT?@{ub}

  Probably going back to the fact that it's a wonderful eco-system. Without 
  doubt it is the best suite of software on the Amiga, no competition. I 
  also admire the way the opened it up with Arexx to allow it to be 
  transformed and integrated by 3rd party developers. There are some unique 
  programs which I would love to explore.

  @{b}11. How would you improve on the VT?@{ub}

  Hmm. Good question.. I still can't work out if you can rotate a brush in 
  Toaster Paint! Some of the documentation is a bit thin on some of the 
  editing tools, so that could have been better. It's also quite easy for 
  sequences to fall out of sync with the audio, and some effects won't 
  trigger if they're too close to another effect. It can feel like you're 
  problem solving more than editing sometimes, but that is often the 
  creative process anyway.

  @{b}12. What parts of the show are you most proud of and why?@{ub}

  I'm most proud of the response from viewers to be honest. It's not for 
  everyone, but those who watch it really enjoy it. There's definitely a 
  long way to go, I would love to make more shows than I do, but I'm 
  totally committed to the show and I'll just keep chipping away.

  From a personal perspective it's been a huge leap to produce something 
  and present it to people. It's going to sound crazy, but I often get 
  embarrassed just by hearing my name mentioned, so this was a big hurdle 
  to jump.

  @{b}13. What advice do you have for others who wish to use the VT for their 
      own videos such as on YouTube?@{ub}

  Do it! It's a really fun process, that makes you re-learn video 
  production. Forget importing mp4s, this is video flying down a mess of 
  cables! And don't forget about the audio, you need cables for all of 
  that too. It can feel a bit intimidating, but draw a quick sketch of the 
  things you need and how they connect, and jump on eBay :D

  It's also possible to create animations in Lightwave for use on your 
  Mac/PC editing software. The Amiga version of Lightwave can render up to 
  8k! With accelerators and emulation, the Amiga can still be used to 
  create something contemporary and (is a) valid creative tool. Going back 
  to these bits of software from a modern perspective can be a revelation. 

  So have fun.

  @{b}14. How many Amigas and non-Amigas do you have?@{ub}

  Oh dear. Here's the confessional. Too many! I have a 1000, 2000, 500+, 
  1200 and CD32. Yikes! And a 500mini. I also use a Mac and PC to encode 
  the video to YouTube, plus off-loading any expensive renders.  I have 
  no issue with emulation. When it comes to rendering, faster is always 
  better. Then I can ftp the frames back to the toaster.

  @{b}15. What is your favorite model of Amiga and why?@{ub}

  I will always have a soft spot for the 500, it was my first Amiga and I 
  loved using it. Playing games, making animations, digitising pictures, 
  and building sequences in Deluxe Video. Good times! But the 2000 has 
  become such a day-to-day workhorse, I have a huge amount of respect for 
  it.

  @{b}16. Do you have any final words or comments before we finish off?@{ub}

  Thanks for watching!
 
@endnode

@node pixelvixen "Pixel Vixen Interview"
@toc talkingamiga
============================================================================
	 @{b}Interview - Pixel Vixel, Manga and Amiga and Artist@{ub}
============================================================================

  @{b}1. Vicky thank you for taking part in our interview, to start off can 
  you tell us a little about yourself?@{ub}

  Well, thank you for having me first of all. I'm from the UK but currently 
  live in north eastern Japan and have been here for nearly 3 years. I'm a 
  keen runner, as well as generally really enjoying retro video games 
  albeit mostly on consoles but I do play games on the Amiga from time to 
  time. I also formerly worked as a wedding photographer but more generally 
  photography is a big part of my life too.

  My main pastime aside from artwork these days is skateboarding, I am 
  currently recovering from breaking my wrist 2 weeks ago so can't draw at 
  all right now. But I spend a lot of time skating and I am hoping one day 
  to create photo projects on the Japanese skate scene.

  And finally, I spend most of my time working on my manga Future Saviors, 
  the story of how three misfits in society find their place in the world 
  and deal with their past to create the future.

  @{b}2. You are known for your manga and computer graphics, which one started 
  first the computer graphics or manga?@{ub}

  Technically manga, if we expand that to include western comics, as I drew 
  comics from a young age. None were ever published obviously, it was 
  little kid stuff, but my favorite character was this rad dog called Dawg. 
  How 90s!

  @{b}3. What was your first computer?@{ub}

  A Commodore 64.

  @{b}4. What made you want to do computer graphics?@{ub}

  Curiosity. So, the second C64 came with an art package and as a keen 
  artist I wanted to see what I could do. It turned out nearly nothing as I 
  only had a joystick to control things. When I got the Amiga that changed. 
  I do know for sure at the time I never looked at computer graphics as a 
  replacement for "traditional" artwork, I just saw it as another method 
  like 	do I do this in copic marker or color pencil kind of thing.

  @{b}5. How you introduced to the Amiga?@{ub}

  That, like so many things in my life as I get older is not 100% clear. 
  But I do remember about three things before I got an Amiga. The first 
  is my cousins. They always had the latest stuff, be it clothes, shoes, 
  music, but also games consoles/computers. My family was relatively poor 
  growing up. I don't even know if I had a C64 when I discovered one summer 
  my cousins had an Amiga 500. We only played games but I remember thinking 
  how good it was. I'm fairly certain that was 1992 as I connect that 
  memory with the Barcelona Olympics; but it's possible it was earlier like 
  1990 or 1991. The second memory is simply all the kids in the playground 
  talking about they now had an Amiga for games and how good it was. That 
  was definitely around 1991/92 as well. The third was a family friend, 
  they had an Amiga 500 and I remember vividly playing Buggy Boy, Rainbow 
  Islands and Jumping Jackson on it. So I was generally aware of the Amiga 
  and through the Silica ads in Zzap 64 and Commodore Format I also knew 
  about the Amiga through that.

  @{b}6. What do you enjoy most about creating graphics on the Amiga?@{ub}

  That's a hard one to answer. I think much of it comes down to simplicity 
  and familiarity. For example I really like Aseprite but Deluxe Paint is 
  just so much simpler on basic things, such as mixing a palette. So 
  despite a lack of layers and multiple undo it's just easier but maybe 
  that's due to familiarity. I also love DPaint's extensive animation 
  capability.

  @{b}7. What is the most challenging part of doing pixel work on the Amiga?@{ub}

  Apart from motivating myself to do it, but then we can all procrastinate
  on a real Amiga, the mouse. I'm sorry but most stock Amiga mice from 
  Commodore are awful, bad ergonomics on the tank mouse and both that and 
  the later mouse Commodore released with the 600/1200/4000 are low 
  resolution ball mice that are just hard to work with. That said, the 
  Amiga 3000 pregnant mouse and the later Amiga Technologies era Amiga 
  mouse are passable. I much prefer the optical mice Alfa Data made.

  @{b}8. Which Amiga art package do you use and why?@{ub}

  Deluxe Paint. Again due to familiarity. On my real Amigas, DPaint IV AGA 
  is my weapon of choice, but I will use III and V. III has the best 
  palette requester, V has some very useful animation capabilities such as 
  multiple palettes and camera control. All suffer from one undo level but 
  you soon get used to it.

  @{b}9. Other than your current Amiga art package, what other Amiga graphics 
     software would like to learn that you haven't yet?@{ub}

  Brilliance II. I have it, at least in the UK but I never got to grips 
  with its UI and the animation power isn't as good as DPaint V but I'd 
  still like to learn it better one day.

  @{b}10. What Amiga hardware do you have/use for your artwork?@{ub}

  In the UK I have an Amiga 500, 600 and 1200. I don't have them here in 
  Japan although someone has loaned me an A600 which I shamefully don't use 
  due to having nowhere to set it up. I hope I can if I move in 2023 though.

  @{b}11. Regarding Your manga Future Saviours, do you use your Amiga at any 
      stage of the creative process?@{ub}

  Yes, after I retreated from the Amiga scene in 2020 for various reasons, 
  I have been quietly building some skills. My impression these days is I 
  don't want the Amiga to be the start and end of the creativity, I want to 
  use bits of it in a wider sense e.g. merging DPaint animations into Final 
  Cut movies, using hand drawn assets, and maybe other new stuff. 
  Essentially to create a trailer or music video but use the Amiga's quirks 
  for an aesthetic. It's something I am in no hurry to finish so it may not 
  see the light of day for a few years.

  @{b}12. In previous interviews you have mentioned using the HAM mode as a 
      creative technique, can you elaborate a bit more on that?@{ub}

  Sure. For me, and others will disagree, I'm not bothered about Amigas 
  (not) having 24bit displays and high resolution, for that I have my 
  MacBook. I want to sit down on a 1MB Amiga 500, and use its HAM mode to 
  generate something that has a charm all of its own that only the Amiga 
  has. So creating glitch animations using hand drawn assets and just 
  generally messing about with it until it looks sick is what I like doing 
  these days. I want it to have a punky edge that looks totally like I'm 
  using the wrong tool but also the right tool that makes it genuinely lo 
  fidelity but full of wonder as a result. I am a big believer in 
  imperfection in life, the imperfect is what makes stuff interesting. 
  Likewise I want to sit down with limitations and push them, this is why 
  I still admire stuff like the cut scenes in Ninja Garden on the 
  Famicom/NES, so many limitations but so much style. This is why I kinda 
  champion the Amiga 600 as it's easy to put 2meg of chip in them and then 
  you can really go mad with animations.

  The reason HAM appeals to me is the way it works to display more colors, 
  it creates sometimes ugly color ramps, but any form of color changing 
  over a few pixels instantly gives an image something unusual. It also 
  means with DPaint you can in effect do transparent brushes over a cel, 
  allowing you to really mess with it.

  @{b}13. What did you find most challenging when moving with your Amiga to 
      Japan?@{ub}

  Well, the fact I couldn't take it! I didn't have room. In the end that 
  has worked out fine; because I believe my future exists in me as an 
  artist, not as that Amiga artist. I emulate these days. But I'll never 
  sell my Amigas and I will one day use them again.

  @{b}14. What is your dream Amiga setup?@{ub}

  Just an Amiga 500 or 600. I am patient so the 68000 doesn't bother me but 
  maybe a 68030 will speed up HAM work a bit. All I need in an Amiga is 2MB 
  chip, some mass storage to save files and that's it; as well as a copy of 
  DPaint. Whilst the A1200 gives me all of the flexibility I need from an 
  Amiga, I prefer the A600s small size, but the A500 is a classic.

  Back when the Amiga was my main computer in the late 90s, 68040s and PPCs 
  with RTG made sense, but now I don't really care about it. I was offered 
  a 68060 card for free once, I turned it down for various reasons but it's 
  wasted on me. There is something pure about sitting down at an Amiga 500 
  with DPaint III and messing around. I think CTrix best encapsulated that 
  vibe with his series on Amiga samplers a year or two back. It was so sick
  really punk.

  @{b}15. Thank you for your time Vicky and the best of luck with your manga 
      series, before we finish up is there anything you would like to add 
      or comment on?@{ub}

  Thank you, it's a pleasure.
  
  To read more from Pixel Vixen a.ka. Vicky check out this issues 
  @{"Shell Talk" link shelltalk} for her perspective on the current Amiga scene.  

@endnode

