@node futureimagineer "Future Imagineer A New Podcast"
@toc contents
============================================================================
	      @{b}Future Imagineer: A New Podcast@{ub} - by: @{"Vicky Lamburn" link vickylamburn}
============================================================================

  In this edition of WhatIFF, you will probably be pretty tired of hearing 
  from me by now what with having an interview, shell talk piece and now 
  this as well? The good news is you can hear even more from me if you tune 
  into my brand new podcast "Future Imagineers".

  Following on from my interests as a creative myself, I decided having 
  written that opinion piece for WhatIff to take matters into my own hands 
  and turn the mic towards creatives using both retro and modern equipment 
  to create interesting and new pieces of artwork, music, photography, 
  publications, video, games and much much more. Rather than be rooted in 
  nostalgia that doesn't move forwards, I wanted to create a podcast to 
  celebrate the active use of this stuff that means it will continue to 
  have relevance in the future and not only be a historical footnote.

  Whilst it won't necessarily be always Amiga centric, it will feature 
  interesting people who not only like older equipment, such as the Amiga, 
  the Yamaha DX7, Akai S900, Nikon FM cameras and goodness know what else, 
  but it will ask them the questions of why their choices are so integral 
  to their creativity. Furthermore, it's about opening this up to an 
  audience way beyond the retro crowd, such as the youth of today so they 
  too can see the possibilities that come of mixing and merging retro and 
  modern technology.

  You can find the podcast on Spotify, and soon Apple Podcasts as well as 
  many others, as well as my YouTube channel (see links below).

  My first guest is Ant Jarvis who talked with the podcast to explain his 
  use of the Newtek VideoToaster to create his beloved Amiga show The Amiga 
  Show on YouTube. From exploring what the kit is, and how he goes about it 
  and what he would do if it broke as well as how he wants to progress the 
  show, it was a very interesting discussion!

  Future Imagineers is intended to be an open door for all creatives to 
  both listen and take part, be they on YouTube and social media or not. No 
  matter what it is you create, be it entirely retro, or a mixture of retro 
  and modern, even including emulation I'd love to hear from you if you 
  fancy being interviewed. You can email the podcast on the details below.

  All enquiries: futureimagineers@outlook.com

  How to listen / watch:

  Future Imagineers YouTube: https://tinyurl.com/futureimagineers-youtube
  Spotify: https://tinyurl.com/futureimagineers-spotify
  Apple Podcasts: https://tinyurl.com/futureimagineers-apple
  Google Podcasts: Please search "Future Imagineers"
      
@endnode

